-- Copper Leads Rebound as Cotton Falls Again: Commodities at Close
-- B y   C l a u d i a   C a r p e n t e r
-- 2013-04-24T16:36:24Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-04-24/copper-leads-rebound-as-cotton-falls-again-commodities-at-close.html
The Standard & Poor’s GSCI gauge of
24 commodities climbed 1 percent to 613.13 by 5:28 p.m. in
London. The UBS Bloomberg CMCI  index  of 26 raw materials was up
0.6 percent at 1,458.063.  BASE METALS  Copper futures jumped the most since September on
speculation that central banks will take more steps to spur
economic growth.  Copper futures for July delivery rose 2.6 percent to
$3.1845 a pound on the Comex in New York. A close at that price
would mark the biggest gain since Sept. 14.  On the London Metal Exchange, copper for delivery in three
months rose 2.3 percent to $7,030 a metric ton ($3.19 a pound).
Aluminum, nickel, zinc, lead and tin also climbed.  Base metals markets: NI BMMKTS  SOFT COMMODITIES  Cotton futures fell to the lowest in eight weeks on
speculation that wet weather boosted crops in the U.S., the
world’s top exporter. Sugar slid, while cocoa, coffee and orange
juice rose.  Cotton for July delivery slumped 2.3 percent to 83.15 cents
a pound on ICE Futures U.S. in New York. Earlier, the price
touched 83 cents, the lowest for a most-active contract since
Feb. 27.  Raw-sugar futures for July delivery slid 1.1 percent to
17.47 cents a pound on ICE, heading for the third straight drop.  Cocoa futures for July delivery rose 0.1 percent to $2,329
a metric ton.  Arabica-coffee futures for July delivery gained 1.2 percent
to $1.3925 a pound. Orange-juice futures for July delivery
jumped 2.2 percent to $1.4475 a pound.  Soft commodities markets: NI SOMKTS  LIVESTOCK  Hog prices advanced the most in a week on signs of
increasing demand for U.S. pork as temperatures rise and
consumers buy more meat for grilling. Cattle also gained.  Hog futures for June settlement gained 1.4 percent to 90.8
cents a pound at 10:12 a.m. on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
heading for the biggest increase for the most-active contract
since April 17.  Cattle futures for June delivery added 0.8 percent to
$1.2185 a pound on the CME.  Feeder-cattle futures for August settlement climbed 1.6
percent to $1.5055 a pound.  Livestock markets: NI LVMKTS  PRECIOUS METALS  Gold rose in New York, rebounding from the first drop in
almost a week, as signs of more physical purchases tempered
shrinking assets in exchange-traded products.  Gold for delivery in June added 0.7 percent to $1,418.80 an
ounce by 7:33 a.m. on the Comex in New York. Bullion for
immediate delivery rose 0.5 percent to $1,420.16 in  London .  Silver for July delivery increased 0.1 percent to $22.895
an ounce, while palladium for June delivery added 0.1 percent to
$674.20 an ounce. Platinum for July delivery advanced 0.3
percent to $1,421.80 an ounce.  Precious metal markets: NI PCMKTS  NATURAL GAS  Natural gas futures declined for a third day in New York as
forecasts showed mild weather that would limit demand for the
heating and power-plant fuel.  Natural gas for May delivery fell 1.3 cents, or 0.3
percent, to $4.225 per million Btu at 10:13 a.m. on the New York
Mercantile Exchange. The futures have climbed 26 percent this
year. Trading volume was 20 percent below the 100-day average
for the time of day.  U.K. natural gas: NI NUKMKT Gas market: NI GASMARKET Americas
natural gas: NI AGASMARKET European natural gas: NI EGASMARKET  GRAINS, OILSEEDS  Corn rose in  Chicago , reversing an earlier decline amid
speculation sowing delays in the U.S. caused by cold and wet
weather will reduce the planted area.  Corn for delivery in July added 0.3 percent to $6.16 a
bushel by 8:26 a.m. on the Chicago Board of Trade on volume near
the average for the past 100 days for that time of day. The
grain earlier fell to $6.10, the lowest since June 26 for a
most-active contract.  Wheat for delivery in July added 0.1 percent to $6.96 a
bushel in Chicago. Milling wheat for delivery in November traded
on NYSE Liffe in Paris fell 0.4 percent to 209 euros ($271.49) a
metric ton.  Soybeans for delivery in July were little changed at
$13.5875 a bushel in Chicago.  Grains markets: NI GRMKTS  OIL PRODUCTS  Gasoline futures rose 0.5 percent to $2.7313 a gallon and
heating oil advanced 1 percent to $2.8395 a gallon, the fifth
consecutive gain.  Oil Products Europe: NI OPEMKT Gasoline: NI GASOLINE Heating
oil: NI HEATOIL  European Carbon Permits  European Union emission permits fell 1.6 percent to 3.03
euros a metric ton.  EU Carbon Emissions: NI ECBMKT  CRUDE OIL  West Texas Intermediate crude rose to a one-week high amid
speculation that the European Central Bank will cut its key
interest rate to a record low. Futures maintained gains after a
report showed that U.S. supplies rose less than analyst
estimated.  WTI crude for June delivery rose $1.59, or 1.8 percent, to
$90.77 a barrel at 11:37 a.m. on the New York Mercantile
Exchange. The contract touched $90.89, the highest price since
April 15. The volume of all futures traded was 13 percent below
the 100-day average for the time of day.  Brent oil for June settlement advanced $1.16, or 1.2
percent, to $101.47 a barrel on the London-based ICE Futures
Europe exchange. The volume of all futures traded was 3 percent
below the 100-day average.  Oil markets: NI OILMARKET  To contact the reporter on this story:
